<p class=3D"mw-empty-elt">
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Plato-4.png" class=3D"mw-file-description"><i=
mg src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/12/Plato-4=
.png/250px-Plato-4.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"250" cla=
ss=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1024" data-file-height=3D"1024"><=
/a><figcaption>A tetrahedron</figcaption></figure>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry" title=3D"Geometry"=
>geometry</a>, a <b>tetrahedron</b> (<abbr title=3D"plural">pl.</abbr>: <b>=
tetrahedra</b> or <b>tetrahedrons</b>), also known as a <b> triangular pyra=
mid</b>, is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polyhedron" title=3D=
"Polyhedron">polyhedron</a> composed of four triangular <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Face_(geometry)" title=3D"Face (geometry)">faces</a>,=
 six straight <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edge_(geometry)" tit=
le=3D"Edge (geometry)">edges</a>, and four <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Vertex_(geometry)" title=3D"Vertex (geometry)">vertices</a>. The t=
etrahedron is the simplest of all the ordinary <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Convex_polytope" title=3D"Convex polytope">convex polyhedra</a=
>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-MW_1-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Tetrahedron#cite_note-MW-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The tetrahedron is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thre=
e-dimensional" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Three-dimensional">three-dime=
nsional</a> case of the more general concept of a <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_geometry" title=3D"Euclidean geometry">Euclidean<=
/a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simplex" title=3D"Simplex">sim=
plex</a>, and may thus also be called a <b>3-simplex</b>.
</p><p>The tetrahedron is one kind of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Pyramid_(geometry)" title=3D"Pyramid (geometry)">pyramid</a>, which is =
a polyhedron with a flat <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polygon" =
title=3D"Polygon">polygon</a> base and triangular faces connecting the base=
 to a common point. In the case of a tetrahedron, the base is a <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Triangle" title=3D"Triangle">triangle</a> (an=
y of the four faces can be considered the base), so a tetrahedron is also k=
nown as a "triangular pyramid".
</p><p>Like all <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convex_polyhedra" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Convex polyhedra">convex polyhedra</a>, a te=
trahedron can be folded from a single sheet of paper. It has two such <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Net_(polyhedron)" title=3D"Net (polyhed=
ron)">nets</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetrahedron#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>For any tetrahedron there exists a sphere (called the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circumsphere" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cir=
cumsphere">circumsphere</a>) on which all four vertices lie, and another sp=
here (the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Insphere" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"Insphere">insphere</a>) <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Tangent" title=3D"Tangent">tangent</a> to the tetrahedron's faces.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Tetrahedron#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
