<p>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_tetrahedron" title=3D=
"Regular tetrahedron">regular tetrahedron</a> is a tetrahedron in which all=
 four faces are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equilateral_triang=
le" title=3D"Equilateral triangle">equilateral triangles</a>. In other word=
s, all of its faces are the same size and shape (congruent) and all edges a=
re the same length. The regular tetrahedron is the simplest <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deltahedron" title=3D"Deltahedron">deltahedron</a=
>, a polyhedron all of whose faces are equilateral triangles; there are sev=
en other convex deltahedra.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTECundy1952_4-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetrahedron#cite_no=
te-FOOTNOTECundy1952-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Irregular_tetrahedra">Irreg=
ular tetrahedra</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DTetrahedron&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: I=
rregular tetrahedra"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bra=
cket">]</span></span></div>
<p>If all three pairs of opposite edges of a tetrahedron are <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perpendicular" title=3D"Perpendicular">perpendic=
ular</a>, then it is called an <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Orthocentric_tetrahedron" title=3D"Orthocentric tetrahedron">orthocentric t=
etrahedron</a></i>. When only one pair of opposite edges are perpendicular,=
 it is called a <i><b>semi-orthocentric tetrahedron</b></i>.
In a <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trirectangular_tetrahedron=
" title=3D"Trirectangular tetrahedron">trirectangular tetrahedron</a></i> t=
he three face angles at <i>one</i> vertex are <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Right_angle" title=3D"Right angle">right angles</a>, as at the =
corner of a cube.
</p><p>An <b>isodynamic tetrahedron</b> is one in which the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cevian" title=3D"Cevian">cevians</a> that join th=
e vertices to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Incircle_and_exc=
ircles_of_a_triangle" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Incircle and excircles=
 of a triangle">incenters</a> of the opposite faces are <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Concurrent_lines" title=3D"Concurrent lines">concurre=
nt</a>.
</p><p>An <b>isogonic tetrahedron</b> has concurrent cevians that join the =
vertices to the points of contact of the opposite faces with the <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inscribed_sphere" title=3D"Inscribed sphere"=
>inscribed sphere</a> of the tetrahedron.
</p>
