data-file-width=3D"918" data-file-height=3D"441"></a><figcaption>A cube dis=
sected into six characteristic orthoschemes.</figcaption></figure>
<p>A <b>3-orthoscheme</b> is a tetrahedron where all four faces are <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Triangle#By_internal_angles" title=3D"Tri=
angle">right triangles</a>. A 3-orthoscheme is not a disphenoid, because it=
s opposite edges are not of equal length. It is not possible to construct a=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disphenoid#Special_cases_and_gene=
ralizations" title=3D"Disphenoid">disphenoid</a> with right triangle or obt=
use triangle faces.
</p><p>An <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schl%C3%A4fli_orthoschem=
e" title=3D"Schl=C3=A4fli orthoscheme">orthoscheme</a> is an irregular <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simplex" title=3D"Simplex">simplex</a>=
 that is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convex_hull" title=3D=
"Convex hull">convex hull</a> of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Tree_(graph_theory)" title=3D"Tree (graph theory)">tree</a> in which all e=
dges are mutually perpendicular. In a 3-dimensional orthoscheme, the tree c=
onsists of three perpendicular edges connecting all four vertices in a line=
ar path that makes two right-angled turns. The 3-orthoscheme is a tetrahedr=
on having two right angles at each of two vertices, so another name for it =
is <i><b>birectangular tetrahedron</b></i>. It is also called a <i><b>quadr=
irectangular</b></i> tetrahedron because it contains four right angles.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Tetrahedron#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Coxeter also calls quadrirectangular tetrahedra "characteristic tetr=
ahedra", because of their integral relationship to the regular polytopes an=
d their symmetry groups.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTECoxeter197371=E2=80=937=
2=C2=A74.7_Characteristic_tetrahedra_6-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetrahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTECoxeter197371%E2%=
80%9372%C2%A74.7_Characteristic_tetrahedra-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For example, the s=
pecial case of a 3-orthoscheme with equal-length perpendicular edges is <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polyhedron#Ancient" title=3D"Polyhedr=
on">characteristic of the cube</a>, which means that the cube can be subdiv=
ided into instances of this orthoscheme. If its three perpendicular edges a=
re of unit length, its remaining edges are two of length <span class=3D"now=
rap">=E2=88=9A<span style=3D"border-top:1px solid; padding:0 0.1em;">2</spa=
n></span> and one of length <span class=3D"nowrap">=E2=88=9A<span style=3D"=
border-top:1px solid; padding:0 0.1em;">3</span></span>, so all its edges a=
re edges or diagonals of the cube. The cube <span style=3D"display:inline-b=
lock;"><span class=3D"mw-default-size skin-invert-image" typeof=3D"mw:File"=
><span><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/b/bd/CDel=
_node_1.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"9" height=3D"23" class=3D"mw-file-=
