<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Space-filling_tetrahedra">S=
pace-filling tetrahedra</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DTetrahedron&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit se=
ction: Space-filling tetrahedra"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A <b>space-filling tetrahedron</b> packs with directly congruent or enan=
tiomorphous (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mirror_image" title=
=3D"Mirror image">mirror image</a>) copies of itself to tile space.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTECoxeter197333=E2=80=9334=C2=A73.1_Congruent_transforma=
tions_9-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tet=
rahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTECoxeter197333%E2%80%9334%C2%A73.1_Congruent_tran=
sformations-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup> The cube can be dissected into six 3-orthoschemes=
, three left-handed and three right-handed (one of each at each cube face),=
 and cubes can fill space, so the characteristic 3-orthoscheme of the cube =
is a space-filling tetrahedron in this sense. (The characteristic orthosche=
me of the cube is one of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hill_=
tetrahedra" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Hill tetrahedra">Hill tetrahedra=
</a>, a family of space-filling tetrahedra. All space-filling tetrahedra ar=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scissors-congruent" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"Scissors-congruent">scissors-congruent</a> to a cube.)
</p><p>A disphenoid can be a space-filling tetrahedron in the directly cong=
ruent sense, as in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disphenoid_=
tetrahedral_honeycomb" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Disphenoid tetrahedra=
l honeycomb">disphenoid tetrahedral honeycomb</a>. Regular tetrahedra, howe=
ver, cannot fill space by themselves (moreover, it is not scissors-congruen=
t to any other polyhedra which can fill the space, see <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hilbert%27s_third_problem" title=3D"Hilbert's third pr=
oblem">Hilbert's third problem</a>). The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Tetrahedral-octahedral_honeycomb" title=3D"Tetrahedral-octahedral ho=
neycomb">tetrahedral-octahedral honeycomb</a> fills space with alternating =
regular tetrahedron cells and regular <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Octahedron" title=3D"Octahedron">octahedron</a> cells in a ratio of 2:1=
.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Fundamental_domains">Fundam=
ental domains</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DTetrahedron&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Fu=
ndamental domains"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brack=
et">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Coxeter-Dynkin_3-space_groups.png" class=3D"m=
w-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/comm=
ons/thumb/a/aa/Coxeter-Dynkin_3-space_groups.png/250px-Coxeter-Dynkin_3-spa=
ce_groups.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"145" class=3D"mw-=
file-element" data-file-width=3D"1046" data-file-height=3D"606"></a><figcap=
tion>For Euclidean 3-space, there are 3 simple and related Goursat tetrahed=
ra. They can be seen as points on and within a cube.</figcaption></figure><=
p>An irregular tetrahedron which is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Fundamental_domain" title=3D"Fundamental domain">fundamental domain</=
a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTECoxeter197363=C2=A74.3_Rotation_groups_in_two=
_dimensions;_notion_of_a_''fundamental_region''_10-0" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetrahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTECoxet=
er197363%C2%A74.3_Rotation_groups_in_two_dimensions;_notion_of_a_''fundamen=
tal_region''-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C=
oxeter_group" title=3D"Coxeter group">symmetry group</a> is an example of a=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goursat_tetrahedron" title=3D"Gou=
rsat tetrahedron">Goursat tetrahedron</a>. The Goursat tetrahedra generate =
all the regular polyhedra (and many other uniform polyhedra) by mirror refl=
ections, a process referred to as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Wythoff_construction" title=3D"Wythoff construction">Wythoff's kaleidoscopi=
c construction</a>.
</p><p>For polyhedra, Wythoff's construction arranges three mirrors at angl=
es to each other, as in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kaleidos=
cope" title=3D"Kaleidoscope">kaleidoscope</a>. Unlike a cylindrical kaleido=
scope, Wythoff's mirrors are located at three faces of a Goursat tetrahedro=
n such that all three mirrors intersect at a single point. (The <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coxeter-Dynkin_diagram" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Coxeter-Dynkin diagram">Coxeter-Dynkin diagram</a> of the generat=
ed polyhedron contains three <i>nodes</i> representing the three mirrors. T=
he dihedral angle between each pair of mirrors is encoded in the diagram, a=
s well as the location of a single <i>generating point</i> which is multipl=
ied by mirror reflections into the vertices of the polyhedron.)
</p><p>Among the Goursat tetrahedra which generate 3-dimensional <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Honeycomb_(geometry)" title=3D"Honeycomb (ge=
ometry)">honeycombs</a> we can recognize an orthoscheme (the characteristic=
 tetrahedron of the cube), a double orthoscheme (the characteristic tetrahe=
dron of the cube face-bonded to its mirror image), and the space-filling di=
sphenoid illustrated <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetrahedron#D=
isphenoid">above</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTECoxeter197371=E2=80=9372=
=C2=A74.7_Characteristic_tetrahedra_6-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetrahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTECoxeter197371%E2%8=
0%9372%C2%A74.7_Characteristic_tetrahedra-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The disphenoid is t=
he double orthoscheme face-bonded to its mirror image (a quadruple orthosch=
eme). Thus all three of these Goursat tetrahedra, and all the polyhedra the=
y generate by reflections, can be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Dissection_into_orthoschemes" title=3D"Dissection into orthoschemes">dissec=
ted into characteristic tetrahedra of the cube</a>.
</p>
<div style=3D"clear:both;" class=3D""></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Subdivision_and_similarity_=
classes">Subdivision and similarity classes</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsecti=
on"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DTetrahedron&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=
=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Subdivision and similarity classes"><span>edit=
</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Tetrahedra subdivision is a process used in computational geometry and 3=
D modeling to divide a tetrahedron into several smaller tetrahedra. This pr=
ocess enhances the complexity and detail of tetrahedral meshes, which is pa=
rticularly beneficial in numerical simulations, finite element analysis, an=
d computer graphics. One of the commonly used subdivision methods is the <b=
>Longest Edge Bisection (LEB)</b>, which identifies the longest edge of the=
 tetrahedron and bisects it at its midpoint, generating two new, smaller te=
trahedra. When this process is repeated multiple times, bisecting all the t=
etrahedra generated in each previous iteration, the process is called itera=
tive LEB.=20
</p><p>A <b>similarity class</b> is the set of tetrahedra with the same geo=
metric shape, regardless of their specific position, orientation, and scale=
. So, any two tetrahedra belonging to the same similarity class may be tran=
sformed to each other by an affine transformation. The outcome of having a =
limited number of similarity classes in iterative subdivision methods is si=
gnificant for computational modeling and simulation. It reduces the variabi=
lity in the shapes and sizes of generated tetrahedra, preventing the format=
ion of highly irregular elements that could compromise simulation results.
</p><p>The iterative LEB of the regular tetrahedron has been shown to produ=
ce only 8 similarity classes. Furthermore, in the case of nearly equilatera=
l tetrahedra where their two longest edges are not connected to each other,=
 and the ratio between their longest and their shortest edge is less than o=
r equal to <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span c=
lass=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none=
;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displays=
tyle {\sqrt {3/2}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <msqrt>
            <mn>3</mn>
            <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
              <mo>/</mo>
            </mrow>
            <mn>2</mn>
          </msqrt>
        </mrow>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle {\sqrt {3/2}}=
}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/9cf43edf8c5bb223b47f1e791713abfe88063cad" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -1.838ex; width:5.811ex; height:4.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle {\s=
qrt {3/2}}}"></span>, the iterated LEB produces no more than 37 similarity =
classes.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Tetrahedron#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"General_properties">General=
 properties</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Tetrahedron&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Gener=
al properties"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
]</span></span></div>
<p>In general, a tetrahedron is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Three-dimensional_space" title=3D"Three-dimensional space">three-dimensiona=
l</a> object with four faces, six edges, and four vertices. It can be consi=
dered as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyramid_(geometry)" title=
=3D"Pyramid (geometry)">pyramid</a> whenever one of its faces can be consid=
ered as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Base_(geometry)" title=
=3D"Base (geometry)">base</a>. Its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Graph_of_a_polytope" title=3D"Graph of a polytope">1-skeleton</a> can be g=
enerally seen as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graph_(discrete=
_mathematics)" title=3D"Graph (discrete mathematics)">graph</a> by <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steinitz%27s_theorem" title=3D"Steinitz's=
 theorem">Steinitz's theorem</a>, known as <b>tetrahedral graph</b>, one of=
 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Platonic_graph" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Platonic graph">Platonic graphs</a>. It is <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complete_graph" title=3D"Complete graph">complet=
e graph</a> <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span =
class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: non=
e;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\display=
style K_{4}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
