            <mn>4</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle K_{4}}</annot=
ation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/fe633da926900748cc19ee1ffec1853834a6c061" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:3.027ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle K_{=
4}}"></span> because every pair of its vertices has a unique edge. In a pla=
ne, this graph can be regarded as a triangle in which three vertices connec=
t to its fourth vertex in the center, known as the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Universal_vertex" title=3D"Universal vertex">universal ver=
tex</a>; hence, the tetrahedral graph is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Wheel_graph" title=3D"Wheel graph">wheel graph</a>.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-FOOTNOTEPisanskiServatius2013[httpsbooksgooglecombooksid3vnEcMCx0HkCpg=
PA21_21]_12-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Tetrahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPisanskiServatius2013[httpsbooksgooglecomboo=
ksid3vnEcMCx0HkCpgPA21_21]-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The tetrahedron is one of the polyhedra that does not have <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Space_diagonal" title=3D"Space diagonal">=
space diagonal</a>; the other polyhedra with such a property are <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cs%C3%A1sz%C3%A1r_polyhedron" title=3D"Cs=C3=
=A1sz=C3=A1r polyhedron">Cs=C3=A1sz=C3=A1r polyhedron</a> and <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schonhardt_polyhedron" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Schonhardt polyhedron">Schonhardt polyhedron</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-FOOTNOTEBagemihl1948_13-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Tetrahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBagemihl1948-13"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It=
 is also known as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simplex" title=
=3D"Simplex">3-simplex</a>, the generalization of a triangle in multi-dimen=
sion. It is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Self-dual" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Self-dual">self-dual</a>, meaning its <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dual_polyhedron" title=3D"Dual polyhedron">dual pol=
yhedron</a> is a tetrahedron itself.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEWohlleben20=
19[httpsbooksgooglecombooksidrEpjDwAAQBAJpgPA485_485]_14-0" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetrahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOT=
EWohlleben2019[httpsbooksgooglecombooksidrEpjDwAAQBAJpgPA485_485]-14"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup> Many other properties of tetrahedra are explicitly described in the =
following sections.
</p>
