the volume is given by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Murakam=
i%E2%80%93Yano_formula" title=3D"Murakami=E2=80=93Yano formula">Murakami=E2=
=80=93Yano formula</a>, after Jun Murakami and Masakazu Yano.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-FOOTNOTEMurakamiYano2005_19-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetrahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMurakamiYano2005-19"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> However, in Euclidean space, scaling a tetrahedron changes its v=
olume but not its dihedral angles, so no such formula can exist.
</p><p>Any two opposite edges of a tetrahedron lie on two <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skew_lines" title=3D"Skew lines">skew lines</a>, an=
