<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Analogous_to_a_triangle">An=
alogous to a triangle</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DTetrahedron&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit sec=
tion: Analogous to a triangle"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edits=
ection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The tetrahedron has many properties analogous to those of a triangle, in=
cluding an insphere, circumsphere, medial tetrahedron, and exspheres. It ha=
s respective centers such as incenter, circumcenter, excenters, <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spieker_circle" title=3D"Spieker circle">Spie=
ker center</a> and points such as a centroid. However, there is generally n=
o orthocenter in the sense of intersecting altitudes.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-20=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetrahedron#=
cite_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaspard_Monge" title=3D"Gas=
pard Monge">Gaspard Monge</a> found a center that exists in every tetrahedr=
on, now known as the <b>Monge point</b>: the point where the six midplanes =
of a tetrahedron intersect. A midplane is defined as a plane that is orthog=
onal to an edge joining any two vertices that also contains the centroid of=
 an opposite edge formed by joining the other two vertices.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-FOOTNOTECrabbs2003_21-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Tetrahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTECrabbs2003-21"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> An =
orthogonal line dropped from the Monge point to any face meets that face at=
 the midpoint of the line segment between that face's orthocenter and the f=
oot of the altitude dropped from the opposite vertex. If the tetrahedron's =
altitudes do intersect, then the Monge point and the orthocenter coincide t=
o give the class of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthocentric_t=
etrahedron" title=3D"Orthocentric tetrahedron">orthocentric tetrahedron</a>=
.
</p><p>A line segment joining a vertex of a tetrahedron with the <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centroid" title=3D"Centroid">centroid</a> of=
 the opposite face is called a <i>median</i> and a line segment joining the=
 midpoints of two opposite edges is called a <i>bimedian</i> of the tetrahe=
dron. Hence, a tetrahedron has four medians and three bimedians. These seve=
n line segments are all <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Concurrent=
_lines" title=3D"Concurrent lines">concurrent</a> at a point called the <i>=
centroid</i> of the tetrahedron.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTELeungSuen199453=
=E2=80=9354_22-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Tetrahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTELeungSuen199453%E2%80%9354-22"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> In addition, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commandino%27s_theo=
rem" title=3D"Commandino's theorem">the four medians are divided in a 3:1 r=
atio by the centroid</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEAlsinaNelsen2015[https=
booksgooglecombooksidFEl2CgAAQBAJpgPA97_97]_23-0" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetrahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTEAlsinaNel=
sen2015[httpsbooksgooglecombooksidFEl2CgAAQBAJpgPA97_97]-23"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Th=
e centroid of a tetrahedron is the midpoint between its Monge point and cir=
cumcenter. These points define the <i>Euler line</i> of the tetrahedron tha=
t is analogous to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euler_line" =
title=3D"Euler line">Euler line</a> of a triangle.
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nine-point_circle" titl=
e=3D"Nine-point circle">nine-point circle</a> of the general triangle has a=
n analogue in the circumsphere of a tetrahedron's medial tetrahedron. It is=
 the <b>twelve-point sphere</b> and besides the centroids of the four faces=
 of the reference tetrahedron, it passes through four substitute <i>Euler p=
oints</i>, one third of the way from the Monge point toward each of the fou=
r vertices. Finally, it passes through the four base points of orthogonal l=
ines dropped from each Euler point to the face not containing the vertex th=
at generated the Euler point.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetrahedron#cite_note-24"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p><p>The center <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline">=
<span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"displa=
y: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle T}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
