<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Integer_tetrahedra">Integer=
 tetrahedra</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Tetrahedron&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D18" title=3D"Edit section: Inte=
ger tetrahedra"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heronian_tetrahedron=
" title=3D"Heronian tetrahedron">Heronian tetrahedron</a></div>
<p>There exist tetrahedra having integer-valued edge lengths, face areas an=
d volume. These are called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heronia=
n_tetrahedron" title=3D"Heronian tetrahedron">Heronian tetrahedra</a>. One =
example has one edge of 896, the opposite edge of 990 and the other four ed=
ges of 1073; two faces are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isoscel=
es_triangle" title=3D"Isosceles triangle">isosceles triangles</a> with area=
s of <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7005436800000000000=E2=
=99=A0"></span>436<span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">800</span></span> and =
the other two are isosceles with areas of <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data=
-sort-value=3D"7004471200000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>47<span style=3D"margin=
-left:.25em;">120</span></span>, while the volume is <span class=3D"nowrap"=
><span data-sort-value=3D"7008124185600000000=E2=99=A0"></span>124<span sty=
le=3D"margin-left:.25em;">185</span><span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">600<=
/span></span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-36" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetrahedron#cite_note-36"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>A tetrahedron can have integer volume and consecutive integers as ed=
ges, an example being the one with edges 6, 7, 8, 9, 10, and 11 and volume =
48.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Sierpinski_37-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetrahedron#cite_note-Sierpinski-37"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
