org/wiki/Roleplaying" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Roleplaying">roleplayi=
ng</a>, this solid is known as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/4=
-sided_die" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"4-sided die">4-sided die</a>, on=
e of the more common <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polyhedral_di=
ce" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Polyhedral dice">polyhedral dice</a>, wi=
th the number rolled appearing around the bottom or on the top vertex. Some=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rubik%27s_Cube" title=3D"Rubik's =
Cube">Rubik's Cube</a>-like puzzles are tetrahedral, such as the <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyraminx" title=3D"Pyraminx">Pyraminx</a> an=
d <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyramorphix" title=3D"Pyramorphi=
x">Pyramorphix</a>.
</p><p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Popular_Culture"></span><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stanley_Kubrick" title=3D"Stanley Kubrick">Stanle=
y Kubrick</a> originally intended the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Monolith_(Space_Odyssey)" title=3D"Monolith (Space Odyssey)">monolith</=
a> in <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2001:_A_Space_Odyssey_(fi=
lm)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"2001: A Space Odyssey (film)">2001: A S=
pace Odyssey</a></i> to be a tetrahedron, according to <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marvin_Minsky" title=3D"Marvin Minsky">Marvin Minsky</=
a>, a cognitive scientist and expert on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Artificial_intelligence" title=3D"Artificial intelligence">artificial=
 intelligence</a> who advised Kubrick on the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/HAL_9000" title=3D"HAL 9000">HAL 9000</a> computer and other asp=
ects of the movie. Kubrick scrapped the idea of using the tetrahedron when =
a viewer who saw footage of it did not recognize what it was, and he did no=
t want anything in the film that regular people did not understand.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-38" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Tetrahedron#cite_note-38"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The tetrahedron with regular faces is a solution to an old puzzle as=
king to form four equilateral triangles using six unbroken matchsticks. The=
 solution places the matchsticks along the edges of a tetrahedron.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-39" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Tetrahedron#cite_note-39"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>38<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
