<p>Several applications of tetrahedra in related fields with engineering ar=
e the following:
</p>
<ul><li>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Numerical_analysis" tit=
le=3D"Numerical analysis">numerical analysis</a>, complicated three-dimensi=
onal shapes are commonly broken down into, or <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Approximate" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Approximate">approx=
imated</a> by, a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polygon_mesh" tit=
le=3D"Polygon mesh">polygonal mesh</a> of irregular <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Tetrahedra" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Tetrahedra">te=
trahedra</a> in the process of setting up the equations for <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Finite_element_analysis" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Finite element analysis">finite element analysis</a> especially in t=
he <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Numerical_solution" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Numerical solution">numerical solution</a> of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Partial_differential_equations" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Partial differential equations">partial differential =
equations</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTERuas2016[httpbooksgooglecombooksi=
dIp4tCwAAQBAJpgPA245_245&amp;ndash;249]6.2.2_Tetrahedron-based_Methods_40-0=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetrahedron#=
cite_note-FOOTNOTERuas2016[httpbooksgooglecombooksidIp4tCwAAQBAJpgPA245_245=
&amp;ndash;249]6.2.2_Tetrahedron-based_Methods-40"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> These method=
s have wide applications in practical applications in <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computational_fluid_dynamics" title=3D"Computational fl=
uid dynamics">computational fluid dynamics</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTE=
Schneider_et_al.2022_41-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Tetrahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTESchneider_et_al.2022-41"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>40<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aerodynamics" title=3D"Aerody=
namics">aerodynamics</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electrom=
agnetic_field" title=3D"Electromagnetic field">electromagnetic fields</a>, =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Civil_engineering" title=3D"Civil =
engineering">civil engineering</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Chemical_engineering" title=3D"Chemical engineering">chemical engineering=
</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naval_architecture" title=3D=
"Naval architecture">naval architecture and engineering</a>, and related fi=
elds.</li>
<li>The tetrahedron is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rigidity_(m=
athematics)" title=3D"Rigidity (mathematics)">inherently rigid</a>.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEWester1997[httpbooksgooglecombooksidFkM0945nFV8CpgPA30=
6_306]_42-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/T=
etrahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTEWester1997[httpbooksgooglecombooksidFkM0945nFV=
8CpgPA306_306]-42"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>41<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For this reason, it is often used to stiffen=
 frame structures such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spacefra=
me" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Spaceframe">spaceframes</a>.</li>
<li>The tetrahedron is used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cal=
trop" title=3D"Caltrop">caltrops</a> to provide an <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Area_denial_weapon" title=3D"Area denial weapon">area deni=
al weapon</a>. This is due to their nature of having a sharp corner that al=
ways points upwards.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBachrach2023[httpbooksgoogl=
ecombooksidVdmzEAAAQBAJpgPA42_42]_43-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetrahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBachrach2023[httpbo=
oksgooglecombooksidVdmzEAAAQBAJpgPA42_42]-43"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>42<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Large steel tetra=
hedra have been used as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anti-tank"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Anti-tank">anti-tank</a> measures,<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEZaloga2013[httpbooksgooglecombooksidMWP3AQAAQBAJpgPT20=
8_208]_44-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/T=
etrahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTEZaloga2013[httpbooksgooglecombooksidMWP3AQAAQB=
AJpgPT208_208]-44"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>43<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> or concrete tetrahedra as <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetrapod_(structure)" title=3D"Tetrapod (structure)"=
>tetrapods</a> to break down waves at coastlines.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNO=
TEParkDodaranHanShahmirzadi2014_45-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetrahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTEParkDodaranHanShahmir=
zadi2014-45"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>44<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>At some <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Airfield" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"Airfield">airfields</a>, a large frame in the shape of a=
 tetrahedron with two sides covered with a thin material is mounted on a ro=
tating pivot and always points into the wind. It is built big enough to be =
seen from the air and is sometimes illuminated.  Its purpose is to serve as=
 a reference to pilots, indicating wind direction.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-46" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetrahedron#cit=
e_note-46"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>45<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Tetrahedral_angle"></span>The tetrahedron c=
an be described as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetrahedral_mol=
ecular_geometry" title=3D"Tetrahedral molecular geometry">tetrahedral molec=
ular geometry</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stereochemist=
ry" title=3D"Stereochemistry">stereochemistry</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTN=
OTEPetrucciHarwoodHerring2002[httpsbooksgooglecombooksidEZEoAAAAYAAJpgPA414=
_413&amp;ndash;414]_47-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Tetrahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPetrucciHarwoodHerring2002[httpsb=
ooksgooglecombooksidEZEoAAAAYAAJpgPA414_413&amp;ndash;414]-47"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 This chemical structure can be found in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Water" title=3D"Water">water</a> <span class=3D"chemf nowrap">H<span=
 class=3D"nowrap"><span style=3D"display:inline-block;margin-bottom:-0.3em;=
vertical-align:-0.4em;line-height:1em;font-size:80%;text-align:left"><sup s=
tyle=3D"font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:baseline"></su=
p><br><sub style=3D"font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:ba=
seline">2</sub></span></span>O</span> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Methane" title=3D"Methane">methane</a> (<span class=3D"chemf nowrap=
">CH<span class=3D"nowrap"><span style=3D"display:inline-block;margin-botto=
m:-0.3em;vertical-align:-0.4em;line-height:1em;font-size:80%;text-align:lef=
t"><sup style=3D"font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align:basel=
ine"></sup><br><sub style=3D"font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical=
-align:baseline">4</sub></span></span></span>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTE=
Bachrach2023[httpbooksgooglecombooksidVdmzEAAAQBAJpgPA43_43]_48-0" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetrahedron#cite_note-=
FOOTNOTEBachrach2023[httpbooksgooglecombooksidVdmzEAAAQBAJpgPA43_43]-48"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>47<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> The tetrahedron shape is seen in nature in <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Covalent_bond" title=3D"Covalent bond">covalently bonded=
</a> molecules. All <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orbital_hybrid=
isation" title=3D"Orbital hybridisation">sp<sup>3</sup>-hybridized</a> atom=
s are surrounded by atoms (or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lone=
_pair" title=3D"Lone pair">lone electron pairs</a>) at the four corners of =
a tetrahedron. For this reason, one of the leading journals in organic chem=
istry is called <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetrahedron_(jo=
urnal)" title=3D"Tetrahedron (journal)">Tetrahedron</a></i>. For a perfect =
tetrahedron, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_angle" ti=
tle=3D"Central angle">central angle</a> between any two vertices is arccos(=
=E2=88=92<span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D=
"num">1</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">3</span><=
/span>=E2=81=A0</span>), or approximately 109.47=C2=B0.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
FOOTNOTEBrittin1945_49-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Tetrahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBrittin1945-49"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>48<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Quaternary <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phase_diagram" t=
itle=3D"Phase diagram">phase diagrams</a> of mixtures of chemical substance=
s are represented graphically as tetrahedra. However, quaternary phase diag=
rams in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Communication_engineering"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Communication engineering">communication en=
gineering</a> are represented graphically on a two-dimensional plane.
</p><p>The vertices of a regular tetrahedron applies as the minimum solutio=
n known for <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span =
class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: non=
e;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\display=
