></span> charged particles on a sphere) and for the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Tammes_problem" title=3D"Tammes problem">Tammes problem</=
a> (of constructing a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spherical_co=
de" title=3D"Spherical code">spherical code</a> maximizing the smallest dis=
tance among the points).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEWhyte1952_50-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetrahedron#cite_no=
te-FOOTNOTEWhyte1952-50"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>If six equal <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Resistor" titl=
e=3D"Resistor">resistors</a> are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S=
older" title=3D"Solder">soldered</a> together to form a tetrahedron, then t=
he resistance measured between any two vertices is half that of one resisto=
r.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-51" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Tetrahedron#cite_note-51"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
50<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Since <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Silicon" title=3D"Silicon">silicon</a> is the most co=
mmon <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Semiconductor" title=3D"Semic=
onductor">semiconductor</a> used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Solid-state_electronics" title=3D"Solid-state electronics">solid-state el=
ectronics</a>, and silicon has a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/V=
alence_(chemistry)" title=3D"Valence (chemistry)">valence</a> of four, the =
tetrahedral shape of the four chemical bonds in silicon is a strong influen=
ce on how <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crystal" title=3D"Crysta=
l">crystals</a> of silicon form and what shapes they assume.
</p><p>Tetrahedra are used in color space conversion algorithms specificall=
y for cases in which the luminance axis diagonally segments the color space=
 (e.g. RGB, CMY).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-52" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetrahedron#cite_note-52"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>51<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetrahedral_hypothesis"=
 title=3D"Tetrahedral hypothesis">tetrahedral hypothesis</a>, originally pu=
blished by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Lowthian_Green"=
 title=3D"William Lowthian Green">William Lowthian Green</a>, explains the =
formation of the Earth with the shape of a tetrahedron.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
53" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetrahedro=
n#cite_note-53"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>52<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> It was popular through the early 20th century.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-54" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Tetrahedron#cite_note-54"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>53<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-55" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetrahedron#cite_no=
te-55"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Related_topics">Related top=
ics</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DTetrahed=
ron&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D20" title=3D"Edit section: Related topi=
cs"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></s=
pan></div>
<p>Regular tetrahedra cannot <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Honey=
comb_(geometry)" title=3D"Honeycomb (geometry)">tessellate space</a> by the=
mselves, although this result seems likely enough that <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aristotle" title=3D"Aristotle">Aristotle</a> claimed i=
t was possible. However, two regular tetrahedra can be combined with an oct=
ahedron, giving a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhombohedron" ti=
tle=3D"Rhombohedron">rhombohedron</a> that can tile space as the <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetrahedral-octahedral_honeycomb" title=3D"T=
etrahedral-octahedral honeycomb">tetrahedral-octahedral honeycomb</a>. On t=
he other hand, several irregular tetrahedra are known, of which copies can =
tile space, for instance, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetr=
ahedron#Orthoschemes">characteristic orthoscheme of the cube</a> and the <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetrahedron#Disphenoid">disphenoid</=
a> of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disphenoid_tetrahedral_h=
oneycomb" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Disphenoid tetrahedral honeycomb">=
disphenoid tetrahedral honeycomb</a>. The complete list remains an open pro=
blem.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTESenechal1981_56-0" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetrahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTESenecha=
l1981-56"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>55<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>If one relaxes the requirement that the tetrahedra be all the same s=
hape, one can tile space using only tetrahedra in many different ways. For =
example, one can divide an octahedron into four identical tetrahedra and co=
mbine them again with two regular ones. (As a side-note: these two kinds of=
 tetrahedron have the same volume.)
</p><p>The tetrahedron is unique among the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Uniform_polyhedron" title=3D"Uniform polyhedron">uniform polyhedra=
</a> in possessing no parallel faces.
</p>
